@deanmalmgren - The code you linked above  https://github.com/deanmalmgren/textract/blob/master/textract/exceptions.py#L69-L76 was broken by this commit: https://github.com/deanmalmgren/textract/commit/ce7bc0ecde56c12a908aae7e454a0fa03236d911#diff-db5f9029a9aa26a0640244cf8f05910aL81

When they removed the "shell=True" argument, that meant that a missing file would throw an OSError on line 80 of that file, instead of running the pipe and returning an exit code 127. This means that there will never be an exit code 127, and thus it will never hit the ShellError.is_not_installed() condition.

I'm assuming that the "shell=True" argument was removed for security reasons (see the warning here: https://docs.python.org/2/library/subprocess.html#popen-constructor ). Re-adding that argument would be the easiest way to resolve this issue, but we could also restructure the code to check for an OSError when the pipe is created and raise some variation of the ShellError.

