There are extra add-ons to make sure javascripthon would work seemly with javascript code. And those add-ons can easily be added to an external package (pyecharts-javascripthon) without waiting for a release of pyecharts. An example is:

```
from pyecharts_javascripthon import Date

def xaxis_formatter(value, index):
    date = Date(value)
    texts = [(date.getMonth() + 1), date.getDate()];
    if index == 0:
        texts.unshift(date.getYear())
    return '/'.join(texts)
```
In the above documentation, Date is javascript entry for Date. Without it, you can hardly use javascript features. In the same category,  these DOM objects are required: Document, window, sessionStorage, localStrorage, cookie...etc. And via pyecharts-scripthon, we reserved the options to add more 3rd javascripts: such as dataframe.js numjs.. or even jQuery.js.. All these small additions will be blocked by pyecharts release.

What's more, I am having a future plan to roll out similiar python to javascript support for python 3.4, 2.7. And this plan would easily work only when the translation interface but not with tight coupling.

