I was able to figure out what was causing the warning. I had a class that was doing something not too smart. This is a greatly simplified version of the class.

```python
class MyClass(object):
    def __getattr__(self, name):
        if not hasattr(self, 'some_field'):
            raise AttributeError()
```

`MyClass` was meant to be subclassed, with subclasses defining the `some_field` attribute. I had a test that asserted that `AttributeError` is raised if `some_field` is not defined. I'm not sure why that doesn't cause infinite recursion, instead of causing that warning message, or why it works in 3.7.1 but not 4.0.0, but there you have it.

